---
import MarketingLayout from "@/layouts/MarketingLayout.astro";
---

<MarketingLayout
  title="About · kino"
  description="Why kino exists, what it doesn't do, who's behind it."
>
  <article class="prose-kino mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight">About kino</h1>

    <p class="mt-6 text-lg text-[var(--color-fg-muted)]">
      kino is a self-hosted media automation and streaming server.
      One Rust binary; nothing extra to wire together. Free software,
      forever.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl font-semibold">Why this exists</h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-[var(--color-fg-muted)]">
      The self-hosted media stack works, but the standard recipe is
      seven separate services in a docker-compose file, each with
      their own database, their own settings page, and their own
      ideas about how to talk to the others. When something breaks,
      you have to know which service owns the problem before you can
      start debugging.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-[var(--color-fg-muted)]">
      kino takes the same set of concerns — discovery, automation,
      library management, transcoding, streaming, casting, privacy
      networking — and puts them in one process behind one UI. One
      database. One log. One thing to update. One thing to back up.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl font-semibold">What kino doesn't do</h2>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-[var(--color-fg-muted)]">
      <li>
        <strong class="text-[var(--color-fg)]">No telemetry</strong>
        — kino contacts no third-party uninvited. The only outbound
        HTTP calls are to services you explicitly configure.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-[var(--color-fg)]">No SaaS tier</strong>
        — there's no paid version, no upsell, no future commercial
        fork. kino is free OSS forever.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-[var(--color-fg)]">No account required</strong>
        — you don't sign up to use kino. There's no central server
        we run. Your install is yours.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-[var(--color-fg)]">No data extraction</strong>
        — your library, watch history, ratings, and config never
        leave your machine unless you explicitly export them.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl font-semibold">License</h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-[var(--color-fg-muted)]">
      kino is licensed under
      <a
        href="https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0"
        class="underline hover:text-[var(--color-fg)]"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
      >GPL-3.0-or-later</a>.
      You can run it for any purpose, modify it, fork it, redistribute
      it. The catch: any derivative work you distribute publicly must
      remain under the same license. This protects every kino user's
      freedom to inspect and modify the software they run, and it
      forecloses the "wrap kino as a paid SaaS" failure mode.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl font-semibold">Who's behind this</h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-[var(--color-fg-muted)]">
      kino is built by a single maintainer (UK-based) with help from
      Anthropic's Claude. Code contributions are welcome — see
      <a
        href="https://github.com/kinostack-app/kino/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md"
        class="underline hover:text-[var(--color-fg)]"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
      >CONTRIBUTING.md</a>.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-[var(--color-fg-muted)]">
      If you'd like to support development financially, the
      <a
        href="https://github.com/sponsors/kinostack-app"
        class="underline hover:text-[var(--color-fg)]"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
      >GitHub Sponsors page</a>
      is the preferred channel. Sponsorship is genuinely appreciated;
      it doesn't unlock anything in the product.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl font-semibold">Naming</h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-[var(--color-fg-muted)]">
      <strong class="text-[var(--color-fg)]">kino</strong>
      is the application — lowercase, like git, vim, ffmpeg.
      <strong class="text-[var(--color-fg)]">kinostack-app</strong>
      is the GitHub organisation that hosts the source.
      <strong class="text-[var(--color-fg)]">kinostack.app</strong>
      is this website.
    </p>
  </article>
</MarketingLayout>
